{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254711/1930062101/0115.xml":{"full_text":"Ora WASHINGTON TIRESi FIH ANCI AL NEWS \u00a3S)\ni_ I \u2014\u2014l\u2014\u2014\u2014\u25a0\u25a0 I. M I\u2014lll,l \u00ab\u2014w i i\nPrices Fluctuate Within Narrow Range With Downward\nHERS FUR\nHE 11\nBLOWS\nLiquidation During Week\nShows Prosperity Blinded\nPeople Coming to Earth\nBjr SPECTATOR\nNEW YORK, June 21.\u2014As pre\ndicted in this 'column yesterday,\nthe rally failed to hold and the\nclose found stocks all through\nthe list showing losses of 1 to\nmore than 10 points. Today\u2019s\nsession, is likely to be a dull af\nfair, with prices fluctuating in a\nsomewhat narrow range and\nfinally closing at still lower levels.\nThe Current nervous uncertainty\nIs likely to influence further sel\nling, by traders who would rather\ntake losses than let long commit\nments stand over the week-end.\nAs matters stand, the technical\nposition of the list is considerably\nbetter than jit was at the close of\ntrading Thursday, and around\ntoday\u2019s lows many stocks will be\nattractive, purchases for trading\nturns. Traders with courage to\nbuy today in anticipation of get\nting profits early next week\nmight do fairly well on the next\nrally. I would warn, however,\nagainst over-extending commit\nments.\nIt is reported on good authority\nthat Electric Bond and Share in\nterests made substantial addi\ntions during the week\u2019s liquida\ntion, to their holdings in affili\nated companies, including Ameri\ncan and Foreign Power, Electric\nPower and Light, American Gas\nand Electric, American Power and\nLight, and National Power and\nLight. Os course, bond and share\ninterests are in a position to\nignore day-to-day fluctuations and\nheld such stocks for the long pull.\nNevertheless, I am inclined to\nbelieve that purchases of leading\npublic utility shares at this time\nwill show handsome profits on\nrallies.\nI\nSome leading bankers profess\nto believe that old line leaders in\nthe stock list have seen their\nlows for a long time to come.\nOn the other hand some im\nportant market operations expect\ngradually declining prices all\nthrough the summer.\nThe liquidation during the last\nweek indicates that many people\nwhose vision had been clouded by\nthe prosperity of war days and\nthe 1928-29 bull market have\nwisely decided to get back to\nearth and a realization of funda\nmental conditions. They are be\nginning to realize that 1929 was\nan abnormal year, that it really\nestablished a peak for all lines of\nbusiness and industry, and that\nnothing in history ever has com\npared with conditions in that\nyear. The sooner this realization\nspreads to the general public, the\nsooner will the country find its\nway back to the path ,of prosper\nity. The struggle back to the path\nwill depend: du hard work, sound\nleadership, foresighted business\nmanagement and closer harmony\nin the nation\u2019s industries.\nWith scores of good stocks sell\ning to yield from 5 per cent to\n8 per. cent, there is a feeling in\nbrokerage circles that bona fide\ninvestors soon will begin to accu\nmulate such issues in quantity.\nAmong the stocks most favored\nby brokers to spurt upward\nsharply on \u2022the next rally are\nAmerican Can, Electric Power and\nLight, International Salt, Public\nService of New Jersey, Consoli\ndated Gas, General Foods,\nVanadium, and United Aircraft.\nHardly a broker in the street\nnames a list of favored stocks\nwithout mentioning all of these.\nAmong those expected to drift\nlower are the chemical and alco\nhol shares, and the amusement\nstocks. Opinion is sharply divided\non the rails.\nInternational Sale recently ex\nperienced a sensational advance,\nfollowing news of a 55 per cent\nincrease in earnings for the first\nfive months of .the year. The new\nshares, representing a three-for\n__A. .J f\nI\nNew York Title and Mortgage Co.\nWashington Branch\n1425 Eye Street N. W.\nThis company is equipped to render prompt title x\nservice in connection with all real estate trans\nactions. Our title certificates and policies of title\ninsurance are backed by our capital funds in\nexcess of 163,000,000.00.\nWe invite your inquiries\nI Honored\nAUBREY O. DOOLEY\nWHO YESTERDAY was ap\npointed to serve as chairman\nof the A. I. B. national pub\nlicity committee.\nPOWER TRUST\nGAVE BRIBES\nRampant bribery lies behind the\nwholesale buying up of munici\npally owned electric plants by the\nPower Trust and by smaller inde\npendent power interests, accord\ning to a batch of confidential\nreports that have come into the\nhands of the Federal Trade Com\nmission.\nThese reports, replete with ref\nerences to \u201coil\u201d and \"sugar\u201d for\ncity councilman, were made by\nbuyers for the defunct W. B. Fo\nshay Utility System and obtained\nby investigators from its offices,\nit was learned yesterday.\nL. E. Lynch, manager of Fo\nshay\u2019s Public Utilities Kansas Cor\nporation, asserted in a report to\nhis home office that \u201ceight out of\nten councils I have contacted dur\ning my brief acquisition experience\ncan only be handled through the\ncoilinr \u2014*\u00abm.\u201d\nHis company and three- others\nwere attempting to persuade the\ntown of Burlington, Colo., to turn\nover its plant to private operators.\nLynch\u2019s report continued:\n\u201cI have been approached by\na man who claims that he can\nhandle the council for a con\nsideration and he assures me\nthat Burlington will be sold\nsoon and advikes that we lose\nno time if we really want to\nacquire the property.\n\u201cI am wondering if it would\nnot be advisable to let the man\nI mentioned handle the matter\nas a broker for a regular\nbrokerage fee. he to handle\nthe fee as he sees fit and if\nit is necessary to apply \u2018oil*\nthat will be a matter of his\nand the councilmen\u2019s consciences\nto decide.\u201d\nTreasury Surplus\nForecast for 1930\nA Treasury surplus of approxi\nmately $140,000,000 was forecast\nyesterday for the close of the fiscal\nyear, June 30.\nPayment of $71,000,000 of in\nterest on the war debts in cash,\ninstead of in securities, has sub\nstantially raised earlier estimates.\nIn addition Treasury experts ex\npressed belief that there will be\nno unusual outlays, by the Farm\nBoard or other agencies, affecting\nthe finances before June 30.\nJune income tax collections up\nto Wednesday night were an\nnounced yesterday as $339,000,000,\nabout $20,000,000 less than on the\nsame date last year. For the lull\nmonth experts anticipated a drop\nof about $40,000,000 from the\n$555,000,000 collections of last\nJune.\none split-up, have been subjected\nto active trading.\nReduction of the rediscount\nrate to 2Vi per cent was viewed\nin some quarters as a bearish de\nvelopment, bn the theory that,\nwith total rediscounts aggregating\nonly $206,794,000 for the Federal\nReserve System and New York\nbanks clear, it must indicate very\npoor business conditions. In any\nevent, the rate cut was ample\nproof that the banking powers\nexpect a protracted period of easy\nmoney.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nMIO-YEfiR LULL\nIN BUSINESS\nAT HAND\nLight-Weight Apparel and\nVacation Goods Spurred;\nSteel Output* Cut Further\nNEW YORK. June 21.\u2014Trade\ni has tended to quiet further and in\nj dustry in several lines has taken\non many of the appearances of\nmidyear slackness, Bradstreet\u2019s\nsaid today.\nThe chief exceptions to the gen\nerally quiet trend were in light\nweight summer wearing apparel\nand vacation goods, owing to sales\nj announced by department stores\nqnd other large retailers, who had\nbegun to lighten stocks, the re\nview stated,\nAccentuating the quieting trend\nsomewhat in the cities was the\ncontinued liquidation in the stock\nmarket, while rural trade was af\nfected by the downward trend of\nfarm products, which generally\nfelt the burden of large stocks or\nthe generally favorable outlook for\nthe growing crops.\nGrains at New Lows\nIn the cereal markets wheat,\ncorn and other grains made new\nlows for the year or longer pe\nriods. Live stock and their prod\nucts were also easier. Iron and\nsteel prices did not ease greatly\nexcept some old materials, while\nin the non ferrous metals, copper\nshowed renewed weakness, de\nclining to pre-war levels.\nThe rally in the stock market\nin mid-week seemed a signal for\nstiffening prices of many com\nmodities with rather better buy\ning of raw materials in many di\nrections.\nA further slowing of output in\nsteel was recorded, with excep\ntional activity in pipe buying and\nheavy structural material evi\ndently more than offset by re\nduced takings of automobile steel\nand other forms in which sea\nsonal quieting is to be expected.\nWool Improves\nSome exceptions to the gen\nerally quiet tone of things com\nmercial were found in the steadi\nness of many grades of wool,\nsome of this re-echoed in a more\noptimistic feeling in worsted\nfabrics.\nIn the industries, the former\nquiet in soft coal continues, with\nlake shipments not large enough\nto offset reduced buying by in\ndustrial users. Furniture manu\nfacturing at leading Southern\npoints partakes of the quiet re\nported in cotton manufacturing,\nin both of which part time is\nquite general.\nLumber reports from the Pacific\nCoast are of large stocks fore\nshadowing shut-downs of opera\ntions while in hardwood sections\nsales and operations were well\nbelow normal.\nCrop reports were more uni\nformly favorable -than at any\nprevious time this year.\nWeek Ended June 14\nDiscloses Upturn\nA sharp upturn in business dur\ning the week ended June 14\nwas reported by the Department\nof Commerce/yesterday.\nCommercial transactions as\nmeasured by the volume of checks\npresented for payments, were\nmore than 6 per cent greater than\nfor the preceding week, and\nwere only 10 per cent under the\nunusually high level of 1929.\nThe volume of building showed\nsubstantial gains over both the\npreceding week and the cor\nresponding week last year.\nCalumet Arizona\nTo Suspend Plant\nNEW YORK. June 21 (1.N.5.).\nCalumet and Arizona Mining Com\npany will suspend operations of\nits leaching and electrolytic plants\nat the New Cornelia mine division\nat AJo.'Ariz., in an effort to secure\nmore economical operation during\nthe present stressed conditions of\nthe copper metal market.\nW. B. HIBBS CO.\nThe ONLY New York Stock Exchange House\nHaving Its Main Office in Washington\n\u2014MEMBERS\nNew York Stock Exchange\nBoston Stock Exchange\nPhiladelphia Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nNew York Cottqn Exchange\nChicago Board of Trade\nAmerican Bankers Association\nDistrict Bankers Association\nHIBBS BUILDING\nNational 0540 WASHINGTON, D. 0.\n\u20141\nWatson, Mellon Open\nAdministration Move\nTo Brighten Business\nA determined Republican cam\npaign, personally directed by\nPresident Hoover and aimed at\nconvincing uneasy business that\nthings are really not as bad as\nthey seem, was put under full\nsteam today.\nThe reassuring statement on\nbusiness conditions made by Sec\nretary Mellon last night, simul\ntaneously with the optimistic\nradio speech of Senator James\nE. Watson, the Senate leader,\nwere merely the opening guns of\nthis campaign. Others will be\nfired at regular intervals while\nbusiness endeavors to digest and\nassimilate the new tariff dish\nset before the country.\nOne of the next steps that will\nbe taken, and before Congress ad\njourns, is the reorganization of\nthe United States Tariff Commis\nsion. New blood is to be brought\nin and the commission energized\nfrom top to bottom.\nAnd following this step. Presi\ndent Hoover plans a few speeches\nTARIFF BATTLE\nSTARTS ON AIR\nVerbal war between Republi\ncan Democratic spokesmen\nover the effects of the Admin\nistration\u2019s new tariff law was un\nder way today with prospects of\ncontinuing intermittently until\nelection day.\nThe opening shot in the tariff\npropaganda battle was fired by\nSenator James E. Watson (R.)\nof Indiana, majority leader of\nthe Senate, who declared the new\nlaw would be vindicated within a\nyear. He admitted the nation\nmight travel a \u201cbumpy road for\na few weeks.\u201d but insisted:\n\u201cSoon normal prosperity will\nbe resumed in the country,\nlargely because of the passage\nof the Smoot-Hawley bill.\"\nWatson made hi s pro-tariff\nspeech over a broadcasting system\nand the Democratic national com\nmittee immediately announced\nthat Senator Pat Harrison (D.) of\nMississippi, a leading opponent of\nthe bill, would speak over the\nsame chain next Tuesday night.\nHarrison said he would specifically\nreply to all of Watson\u2019s claims\nfor the bill.\nThe Indiana Senator ridiculed\ncharges made against the bill.\nHe recited how Democrats had\nmade the same dire predictions of\ndisaster following enactment of\nthe Fordney-McCumber bill in\n1922. Then he gave statistics\nshowing the improvement of\nbusiness and economic conditions\nunder operations of that law.\nRubber Stocks Cut\nSharply Since April\nNEW YORK, June 21.\u2014Stocks\nof crude rubber on Far Eastern\nestates in May amounted to\n12,577 tons, compared with 23.984\ntons at the end of April, accord\ning to figures cabled to the rub\nber exchange of New York.\nThese figures are of more than\nordinary interest, owing to the\nsuspension of tapping on estates\nduring that month under the\nself-imposed restriction plan.\nDealers\u2019 stocks at the end of\nMay totaled 51,393 tons, the cable\nshowed, compared with 55.654\ntons at the end of April. Pro\nduction declared on estates of\nover 100 acres amounted to only\n3,844 tons, as against 18,849 tons\ndeclared during April. Figures for\nestates smaller than 100 acres\nare not given.\nBoard, of governors of the rub\nber exchange have voted that\nSaturday, July 5, as well as July\n4. will be declared a holiday on\nthe exchange.*\nOklahoma Oil Men\nApprove Proration\nNEW YORK. June 21 (1.N.5.).\nOklahoma oil operators approve\nproration program to hold the\nproduction at 650,000 barrels daily\nduring the third quarter of 1930.\nTAa National Daily\nto the country himself as to gen\neral business conditions and the\nI outlook for the future.\nThroughout the summer there\nwill be a steady hammering away\non the thesis of good business\u201d\nand the \u201creturn of prosperity\u201d\nthrough the agency of the Hawley-\nSmoot tariff bill. The Democrats\nhave already accepted the issue\nand shaped their own plans ac\ncordingly.\nSecretary Mellon\u2019s statement\nwas the first he has made in\nsome months concerning the\nbusiness outlook. Throughout the\nperiod of depression and the suc\ncessive crashes in Wall Street,\nMellon has maintained a studious\nsilence.\nBy inference. Secretary Mellon\nsought to place much of the re\nsponsibility for recent depression\nupon the uncertainty produced\n*by the 15 months wrangling over\nthe tariff bill. The Secretary\ncautiously observed, however, that\nhe did not \u201cmean to imply that\nthe bill is free from defects.\u201d\nBUSINESS SLOW\nTO RECOVER\nHARTFORD, Conn., June 21.\u2014\nThe recovery of business in the\nUnited States has been slower\nthan forecasts for the year 1930\nindicated. The first months of\n1930 have witnessed a movement\ntowards normalcy, but this trend\nhas been gradual.\nWhen this slow, rather uncer\ntain growth is compared to the\nbooming prosperity of a year ago\nit makes present business seem\nmore inactive that it actually is.\nAs yet there is no basis for the\nprophecies of an extended period\nof depression, that have been ad\nvanced.\nBusiness is being retarded in\nits recovery by sevAal political\nfactors. The unsettled political\nconditions in this country and\nabroad are a depressing influence.\nThe new tariff will undoubtedly\ncause a raised duty on our goods\nin several foreign countries. Ex\nports for the first part of 1930\nare considerably below those of\na year ago, due in part, at least,\nto world conditions, such as the\ncivil war in China, the trouble in\nIndia.\nBorden Co. Acquires\nTwo New Properties\nNEW YORK. June 21 (IN.SJ.\nThe Borden Company has acquired\nJessup and Antrim Ice Cream\nCompany, of Indianapolis, for\n6,000 shares of Borden capital\nstock, and Cairns Creameries. Ltd,,\nof Niagara Fails. Ontario, for\n3,481 shares of stock.\nThe listing of these 9,481 shares\nof additional stock will bring Bor\nden\u2019s total outstanding capital up\nto 4,065,972 shares of $25 par cap\nital stock.\nChicago Bank Cuts\nRediscount to 3% P\u00bbC.\nThe Federal Reserve Bank in\nChicago has reduced its rediscount\nrate from 4 to 3Vi per cent, effec\ntive today, the Federal Reserve\nBoard announced yesterday.\nThe New York member bank yes\nterday dropped its rate to 2Vi per\ncent\u2014the lowest \u00abince the board\nwas organized\u2014and the Cleveland\nand Boston banks are on a 3Vi per\ncept basis, with the others still\nkeeping the 4 per cent rate.\nTROUSERS\nTo Match Your Odd Coats\nEISEMAN\u2019S, 7th F\nTime Tables\nNever Bother\nVacationists\nwho know\nthe convenience\nof traveling in a\ncar of their own.\nUnusual oppor\ntunities to invest\nin GOOD used\ncar transporta\ntion are listed in\ntoday\u2019s\nTimes Classified Ads\n\nLAST WEEK\nCONVICT\nSHIP\nSATURDAY, JUNE 21, 1930\nNORTH-SOUTH\nIINE ON COAST\nAPPROVED\nI. C. C. Action to Give Great\nNorthern and West. Pacific\nAccess to New Territory\nHt Universal Nervier\nApproval was given by the In\nterstate Commerce Commission\nyesterday to the $13,000,000 con\nstruction project of the Great\nNorthern and Western Pacific for\na new Oregon-California line to\nlink Klamath Falls with San\nFrancisco.\nThe commission\u2019s order author\nizes the Great Northern to con\nstruct 88 miles of road in Kla\nmath county. Oregon, and Siski\nyou. Modoc and Lassen counties.\nCalifornia.\nThe Western Pacific is author\nized to build 112 miles in Plumas,\nLassen and Modoc counties, and\ngives it trackage rights over a\nportion of the Great Northern\nline.\nThe Great Northern part of the\nproject will call for an investment\nof $3,350,000 and that of the\nWestern Pacific $9,800,000.\nThe Western Pacific line is to\nextend from Paxton on its main\nline to Keddie, the terminus of a\nbranch line from Paxton in\nPlumas county, north through\nLassen county to Lookout on Pit\nRiver in the southwest comer of\nModoc county, where it will tie up\nwith the Great Northern line.\nThe threefold effect of this\n200-mile project will be to give\nthe Great Northern an entrance\ninto the San Francisco territory\nover the Western Pacific and the\nWestern Pacific an entrance into\nSouthern Oregon, besides open\ning up a vast area in Northern\nCalifornia not now served by\nrail transportation.\nThe project has been bitterly\nopposed before the commission\nby the Southern Pacific, which\ncontended it provided all the\nrail facilities the affected terri\ntory required and would support.\nThe commission did not take this\nview, however, declaring:\n\u201cUpon the facts presented we\nfind that the present and fu\nture public convenience and ne\ncessity require the construc\ntion and operation of the lines\nof railroad described by the ap\nplicants in their separate ap\nplications and the joint con\nstruction and for acquisition\nand joint operation of the line\nof railroad described in their\noint application. Permission\nto retain excess earnings will\nbe denied.\u201d\nMachine Firm Sells\nLaundry Division\nGeneral Laundry Machinery\nCorporation announces that ne\ngotiations have been completed\nfor the sale of its laundry ma\nchinery division to the American\nLaundry Machinery Company. A\nspecial stockholders meeting has\nbeen called for June 27 for formal\napproval of the sale, and to vote\non changing the name to the\nTolhurst Corporation.\nThe acquisition is for an out\nright cash consideration reported\nto be well in excess of $1,000,000\npart of which it is expected will\nbe used to retire the Corpora\ntion\u2019s 6Vi per. cent, gold notes.\nAT YOUR TH EATER TONIGHT\nOFFICIAL PROGRAMS of Theater Members of the\nMotion Picture Theater Owners of District of Columbia\nFOX F at Fourteenth\nWill Rogers In \u201cSo This Is I\u00abndon\u201d\nwith Irene Rich\nStage\u2014Fanchon and Marco Idea\u2014\n\u201cROT DOMINOES.\" Sam Jack\nKaufman, Master of Ceremonies\nFOX ORCHESTRA\nFOX MOVIETONE NEWS\nL PALACE\u2014f St. it 13th\nMarton Davies in \u201cThe Florodort*\nGirl.\" Stage\u2014Henry Bergman In\n\u201cBlack Sheep.\" Hearst Metrotone\nE News. Short Subjects. Palace Or\nchestra. Added. \u2018Killing the Killer\u2019\nw COLUMBIA\u2014FSt. at 12th\n\u201cWITH BYRD AT THE\nS SOUTH POLE\"\nShort Subjects. Hearst Metro\ntone News. Columbia Orchestra\nR-K-0 KEITHS r*w\u00ab\nJEAN HERSHOLT In \u201cMAMBA.\u2019\u2019 with\nEleanor Boardman and Ralph Forbes\nUsual Subsidiary Offerings\nTA If All A Fourth arid Butternut.\nlARUmfI Tahoma Park. D. C.\nTalking Pictures at Their Best\nRIN-TIN-TIN in \u201cMAN HUNTER\u201d\nAlso \u201cTHREE SISTERS\"\nJ- LINCOLN\n1 Dennis King A Jeanette MacDonald\nan in \u201cThe Vagabond King\"\nH BOOKER T \u00dcB3 Talkie?\u2019 W\nT HAMON NOVARRO.\nin \u201cIN GAY MADRID\"\nA ROSALIA\nLEILA HYAMB In \"Harrlcape\"\nBROADWAY **V> W\nS LUTE VELES hi \u201cHell Harbor**\nRetires\n'-'fy 'O\n9 989.\n\n1 Ha\nK JJF\u2019\n9 Br\nAUGUST H. PLUGGE\n'WHO HAS just retired as\npresident of the Seventh Street\nSavings Bank to become chair\nman of the board. John D.\nHoward succeeds him. Directors\nalso have voted 6 per cent semi\nannual dividend.\n\u25a0\u201cUSTINGS\nANNOUNCED\nNEW YORK, June 21.\u2014Board\nof governors of the curb ex\nchange has approved the ad\nmittance to unlisted trading priv\nileges of the following securities:\nCommonwealth Securities, Inc.,\n2.000.000 shares no-par- common\nstock: Motor Banker Corporation.\n500.000 shares no-par common:\nMinnesota Northern Power Com\npany, 800.000 shares no-par com\nmon: Saxet Company, 1,000,000\nshares no-par common. Fairchild\nAviation Corporation, rights to\nsubscribe for shares of capital\nstock of Aviation Corporation of\nDelaware, when, as and if issued\nin accordance with the plan as set\nforth in notice of stockholders.\nAlso Pacific Investing Corp.,\n250,000 shares no-par common\nand 60,000 shares of cumulative\nfirst prefererd stock, par value\n$100; National Securities Invest\nment Company, 1,500,000 shares\nsl-par common stock: Southwest\nern Gas and Electric Company,\n100,000 shares of 7 per cent\ncumulative preferred stock, par\nSIOO.\nThe following securities were\nremoved from the unlisted trading\nlist:\nHamilton Watch Company, old\ncommon stock, par value $25. new\ncommon stock, without par value,\nwhen, as and if issued; Super\nheater Company, capital stock,\nno-par value; Mead Pulp and\nPaper Company, certificates of\ndeposit for common stock.\nAbandonment Plea\nOs Ohio Line Denied\nThe Interstate Commerce Com\nmission yesterday denied the ap\nplication of the Pennsylvania,\nOhio and Detroit railroad to\nabandon its Montgomery branch\nin Hamilton county, Ohio, and\nthe abandonment of operation of\nthe branch by the Pennsylvania\nrailroad.\nWARNER BROS. THEATERS\nAMBASSADOR\nWILLIAM BOLD\nin OFFICER O\u2019BRIEN\u201d\nVitaphone Variety\nAPOLLO Northeast I\nMONTE B L U E\nin \u201cTHOSE WHO DANCE\u201d\nComedy\nAVAI AN Connecticut Are. and\nAIALUU McKinley St.. D- C.\nRIN TIN TIN\ntn \u201cROUGH WATERS'*\nVitaphone Variety Comedy\nAVENUE GRAND\nRICHARD ARLEN in\n\u2022\u2022THE LIGHT OF WESTERN STARS\u201d\nComedy\nCFHTRAI Ninth St. Between\n\u00dcbRIIIHL d and E Sts.\nRAMON NOVARRO\nin \u201cIN GAY MADRID\u201d\nVitaphone Variety\nCOLONY e \u00b0Fawagut\"st BBd I\nJACK; MULHALL\nin \u201cIN THE NEXT ROOM\"\nVitaphone Variety\n\nDCD||D| IP St- Nunr 14th\nnCrUDLIV Phone North ISM\nBILLIE DOVE and CLtVE BROOK\nfa \"Sweethearts and Wives\u2019\u2019\nUSE DE TRUCKS\nSEEN AS PERIL\n1 TO RAILWAYS.\nPennsy Official Cites Steady\nDrop in Less-Than-Carload\nFreight Hauls Since 1920\nATLANTIC CITY, N. J., June\n21.\u2014Increased utilization of mo\ntor trucks for the movement of\nfreight provides a serious prob\nlem for the railroads, according\nto R. K. Stackhouse, of Philadel\nphia, general superintendent of\nstations and transfer, Pennsylva\nnia railroad.\nAs to what should be done to\nmeet motor truck competition,\nMr. Stackhouse said, addressing\nthe closing session here yesterday\nof the convention of the Motor\nTransport Division of the Ameri\ncan Railway Association, it is\nfelt this feature divides itself into\ntwo phases: First, expeditious\nmovement of traffic by railways,\nand, second, what may be done\nin highway motor trucking. He\nadded:\n\u201cThe effect of motor tracks\non railway movement is shown\nby the fact that in 1920, Class\nA steam railways handled 89<\n901,149 tons of less than car\nload lot freight; in 1926 it had\ndropped to 68,296,686 tons, a de\ncrease of 24.03 per cent.\nDrops Steadily\n\u201cIn 1928 it had further de\nclined to 63,260,249 tons, a de\ncrease of 29.7 per cent from\n1920. The motor track has\nbeen a potent factor in less\nthan carload lot freight haul\nage, and each railroad has no\ndoubt determined the extent to\nwhich this feature affects its\nrevenues.\n\u201cThe number of trucks regis-*\ntered in the United States rep\nresents a barometer of motor\ntrack progress. At the end of\n1920 there were 1,006,082 trucks\nregistered, while on the same\nday in 1925, there were 2,441,-\n709, an increase of 143 per cent\nover 1920. On the last day of\n1929, there were registered la\nthe United States, 3,379,854 mo\ntor trucks, an increase of 38\nper cent over 1925.\n\u201cTruck production by capaci\nties in 1929, which was a fairly\nrepresentative year, showed that\n93.4 per cent of the total pro\nduction consisted of trucks of:\nless than than two and one\nhalf tons. Trucks of from two\nand one-half tons and less than\nfive tons amounted to 5.1 per\ncent, while 1.5 per cent of the\ntotal production were trucks of\nfive tons and over.\nTerminal Use Lead\n\u201cA natural indication from\nthese figures would be that the\nmotor track performs its most\nvaluable service in terminal\nareas. However, although 93\ncent of the tracks are of less\nthan two and one-half tons ca\npacity, a great deal of com\nparatively long distance traffic\nundoubtedly is? carried on such\ntrucks.\n\u201cFurthermore, those smaller\ntrucks, when considered in con\njunction with the number of\nlarge capacity trucks, and the\nvarious types of trailers (includ\ning the special trailer for auto\nmobile handling), constitute in\nthe aggregate a vast potential\nity in the transportation of\nfreight.\u201d\nFA PI f Thirteenth Street\nBelow F Street\nIn Person, Gus Edwards, Star Maker\nA Composer, and Armide. Petite Film\nStar. On the Screen\u2014Reginald Denny In\n\"What a Man Added Short Subjects\nUflllF 1:M c strr\nVIH Si Northeast\nW ILLI A M B OY D\nin \"OFFICER O'BRIEN\u201d\nCartocn. \u201cThe Jade Box\u201d No.J\nMETROPOLITAN\nJACK OAKIE and MARY BRIAN\nin \u201cTHE SOCIAL LION\nVitaphone Varieties\nSAVOY n!4th and Rd.\nMARY P'HILBIN\nin \"AFTER THE FOG\nI Vitaphone Variety\nTIVOLI t4th Northwest B\nt Return Engagement of\n\u201cTHE GOLD DIGGERS\nOF BROADWAY\u201d\ni i\nVft\u00dflf Georgia Avenue and\nI Ulin Quebec Street.\nRICHARD ARLEN in\n\"THE LIGHT OF WESTERN STARS\nComedy\nSTATE\nWestern Electric Sound System\nSue Carol. Dixie Lee A Walter Catlett\nin \u201cTHE BIG PARTY\u201d\n15","height":"30325","width":"24399"}}
